segments.text: headed that until the early 60s.
And in, I believe it is 62, according to the news, T's news, he's listed as director of the Engineering Experiment Station.
Kahan?
Yeah, Kahan.
Yes.
I believe he handled that and the Research Foundation together.
And of course, the operations were small.
Then he went to Oklahoma, and I think he went to the University of Oklahoma on that stick, and took charge of their research foundation.
Dean Benson was in charge of it, and then they kind of put him in charge, and then Benson took it back again?
I guess so, yes.
That's the engineering experience.
And he took it back again alongside his duties as dean of engineering.
And TTI.
Yes, that's right.
He was the executive officer of the Texas Transportation Institute, two or three agencies.
Did you see much of him, or was he?
Oh, yes, he was.
He was in everything.
Once in a while, you'd see him around.
Because he had so many different jobs he was doing, he wondered if he ever had time to get out of his office.
Oh, yes.
Because I gave him the research foundation in the mid-'60s, too.
Between the time you came here in the mid-'40s to the time you went to TTI,
Do you remember any time of big change or a low point in Texas Engineering Experiment Station?
I don't really remember a low point.
Nobody else has either.
Did you have any dealings through your role in TEAS, in the education at A&M, educating students?
Or was that separate from yours?
Well, I'll tell you.
Students have always found their way to my office, graduate students especially.
And I've helped graduate students through the years with the literature they've needed for their research.
And it would be usually the literature from the shelves.
And they would use this in the research.
They'd come by, and everybody knew of Mr. Horn.
Everybody had that.
He might have that, yes.
We'd have to get it.
Speaking of he might have that, everyone says you might have some of the early pictures or know where they are.
that you used in the journal?
Yes.
Those would be at the Photographic and Visual Aids Lab.
They would have a file of the magazine.
The university's lab?
Yes, ma'am.
OK. That's where we had the pictures made at the time.
We'd use their photographers.
OK.
So we'd like to use some of those pictures again in this history.
We've got to find it first.
Do you know where that lab is right now?
It's...
I don't know how you... Oh, yeah.
Go to the printing center.
They have a clerk in the front office of the printing center, and she'll handle your work, or one of those ladies up there will handle your work.
And if you need to go back to the files while that lady would escort you back,
into the photographic laboratory and you could look back there.
Is there anything else you remember about your time at T's?
Any other great stories you'd like to tell?
It was all great work.
I enjoyed it.
I appreciated them and I think they appreciated me.
We got along great through the years.
I just, somewhere along the line, I just found an opportunity to get a little more salary.
My salary became unclassified.
Earlier it was classified.
When I first started classifying salaries, so I
To get unclassified, I had to go over into the Texas Transportation Institute.
Well, I appreciate your time today.
